THAT the First Book of the Epistles of Horace was published as a whole seems to be shown by the introductory character of Ep. i. and still more plainly by the language of Ep. xx. Such a course would be, as Bentley proved, quite in accordance with the prac- tice of Horace himself, and of contemporary poets. The date of publication appears at first sight to be given precisely by the closing lines of the last Epistle.

Forte meum si quis te percontabitur aevum, me quater undenos sciat implevisse Decembres, collegam Lepidum quo duxit Lollius anno.
